Problem Statement

A retail store provides discounts based on the total purchase amount according to the following scheme:

Purchase Range (Rs)	Discount Percentage
1000 – 5000	10%
5001 – 10000	20%
Above 10000	25%
Equivalence Classes

Valid Classes:

Class ID	Range	Discount
VC1	1000 – 5000	10%
VC2	5001 – 10000	20%
VC3	>10000	25%

Invalid Classes:

Class ID	Range / Condition	Result
IC1	<1000	No Discount
IC2	= 0	Invalid
IC3	< 0	Invalid (Negative value)
IC4	Non-numeric input	Invalid input
Boundary Value Analysis (BVA)

Boundaries Identified:

Range	Lower Boundary	Upper Boundary
VC1	1000	5000
VC2	5001	10000
VC3	10001	-

Boundary Test Values:
999, 1000, 1001, 4999, 5000, 5001, 9999, 10000, 10001

Test Cases
Test ID	Purchase Amount (Rs)	Expected Discount (%)	Expected Final Amount (Rs)	Expected Result	Test Type	Remarks
TC1	0	0%	–	Invalid Input	Boundary	Zero value
TC2	-500	0%	–	Invalid Input	Boundary	Negative value
TC3	999	0%	999	No Discount	BVA	Just below valid range
TC4	1000	10%	900	Valid	BVA	Lower boundary VC1
TC5	1001	10%	900.90	Valid	BVA	Just above lower boundary
TC6	3000	10%	2700	Valid	EP	Mid value VC1
TC7	4999	10%	4499.10	Valid	BVA	Just below upper boundary VC1
TC8	5000	10%	4500	Valid	BVA	Upper boundary VC1
TC9	5001	20%	4000.80	Valid	BVA	Lower boundary VC2
TC10	7500	20%	6000	Valid	EP	Mid value VC2
TC11	9999	20%	7999.20	Valid	BVA	Just below upper boundary VC2
TC12	10000	20%	8000	Valid	BVA	Upper boundary VC2
TC13	10001	25%	7500.75	Valid	BVA	Lower boundary VC3
TC14	15000	25%	11250	Valid	EP	Mid value VC3
TC15	50000	25%	37500	Valid	EP	Large purchase amount
TC16	"ABC"	–	–	Invalid Input	EP	Non-numeric
TC17	2500.50	10%	2250.45	Valid	EP	Decimal amount
Calculation Examples

Example 1:
Purchase = 5000
→ Discount = 10% × 5000 = 500
→ Final Amount = 5000 - 500 = 4500 Rs

Example 2:
Purchase = 10001
→ Discount = 25% × 10001 = 2500.25
→ Final Amount = 10001 - 2500.25 = 7500.75 Rs
